Have spent roughly seven hours over the past month looking for Pheasants reported recently in the Bamberg area.  Finally located at pinned location at edge of forest along roadside.  At a time when the status of RNPH in Ontario is of question, I think the following points are necessary to justify a self-sustaining population. This is by no means conclusive evidence and will adjust report if new evidence is found. Some points towards a naturalized exotic:  -	Nearest known Pheasantry (Creekside Pheasantry) is located 10 km away and no evidence of captive birds from local homeowners -	From eBird and word of mouth, male and females have occurred in all seasons in this region since the 80’s and possibly earlier -	There is at least one male that has been seen three times along Moser Young Road between Bamberg and Gerber Road in the last month -	Behaviour reflective of a natural bird (very skulky, tangle jumping)  As far as I’m aware this is the last promising population of Pheasants left in Waterloo Region.

Shortly after I arrived at the preserve and after walking a very short distance past the kiosk, a bright red head popped up out of the grass. Awestruck, I slowly raised my camera with hopes that this incredibly beautiful bird would stay. And it did. The male Ring-necked Pheasant walked slowly through the grass heading toward the north and disappeared into the woods where it gave an occasional (quite loud) cry. (Please see photos).

Have spent roughly seven hours over the past month looking for Pheasants reported recently in the Bamberg area.  Finally located at pinned location at edge of forest along roadside.  At a time when the status of RNPH in Ontario is of question, I think the following points are necessary to justify a self-sustaining population. This is by no means conclusive evidence and will adjust report if new evidence is found. Some points towards a naturalized exotic:  -	Nearest known Pheasantry (Creekside Pheasantry) is located 10 km away and no evidence of captive birds from local homeowners -	From eBird and word of mouth, male and females have occurred in all seasons in this region since the 80’s and possibly earlier -	There is at least one male that has been seen three times along Moser Young Road between Bamberg and Gerber Road in the last month -	Behaviour reflective of a natural bird (very skulky, tangle jumping)  As far as I’m aware this is the last promising population of Pheasants left in Waterloo Region.

New yard lifer. It browsed between 3 corner garden plots, running into the one with berries that was a great cover, when a car drove past. It was amazing to see how well the pheasant disappeared into a tiny garden plot! It walked straight toward me while I was sitting on the lawn watching it, at my head level (since I was sitting low). I'm so surprised I was able to sit out in the open and watch it but my face was partially obscured by my camera lens so I think it genuinely didn't notice me. None of these photos are cropped. This is just how close it was to me.

In case anyone was doubting I actually saw one in my backyard in the city the other day, here is proof haha.  Still not great pictures but decent.  Was unable to position well on the bird since I didn't want to startle it after I already noticed it.  Was observing the Spotted Doves this morning as I noticed an orange patch of feathers in the vines along the brick wall in our backyard, at first I thought maybe it was a squirrel, but then it popped its head up at the sound of my shutter and so I started snapping more pictures.  Stayed their feeding for about 5 minutes as I stood motionless, eventually flew off and away into a different neighbors backyard when it was startled by a loud bang.  I am very curious as to why it would be around this part of the city as I haven't seen a sighting recorded in the city anywhere in the Central Valley.  Always on outskirts and outlying farmland.  Since its still here from original sighting that means it has been sticking around in the area for at least 2-3 days.  I will see if it comes back again.  I haven't heard it call in the whole time I have been here so it's quite secretive.

Observation Details: For several years we've been seeing Ring-necked Pheasants along Old Vinton Road near Prairie Wildlife northeast of West Point and know that they release some every year for hunters staying at their lodge. This pheasant I was surprised to see back in March 2016 at the Overlook of Columbus Lake near the Tombigbee Waterway Lock and Dam there. The two areas are only about 15 miles apart if the bird traveled in a fairly straight path from Old Vinton Road to the Columbus Lake area, so I assumed this bird had traveled from there. I'll add some photos I took back on March 12, 2016. I've never seen a pheasant again in that area. But when we bird on Old Vinton Road, we usually see 2 or 3 pheasants along the road, both male and female. So we wonder if there is any chance they have begun nesting in the wild in that area.

Locality: Merced NWR--Auto Tour Route (4.8-mile one-way loop road)

Observation Details: Deju vu! Likely the same RINP we observed in the same area 6-1/2 mons. ago on Oct. 24, 2016. We had just parked the car opposite the field, intending to walk north through woods to the Charles River, when we heard the unmistakable crowing call of a male pheasant. We decided to move on. Later, when we returned to the car, we heard the call again from across Hospital Rd. (Medfield, MA) . We followed the path below "Hospital Hill." As we walked, the hidden pheasant appeared to follow us in the woods next to the path, calling several times from the woods, always opposite us. As we started back, the bird suddenly walked out onto the path 15-20 ft. in front of us. We stood still as the pheasant  walked ahead of us. As before, I was able to snap several images before the bird walked back into the brush. The observation took place very close to where we saw a walking male RINP last Oct. (See Checklist S32229530.)

Two male pheasants were foraging near roadside; one was a typical Ring-necked Pheasant. The other, here, was darker and I suspected it could be a hybrid between Green and Ring-necked Pheasant. Although perhaps it is a melanistic, domestic-form Ring-necked Pheasant (in which case could be reported as the domestic form). A local reviewer contacted me and suggested it is an integrade between the regular and the all blue or melanistic form of RNPH, if I understood him correctly.  It had purple head and breast. The dark purple color on breast extended to lower breast but lower belly and vent were rufous with purple flecks, unlike Green Pheasant and similar to Ring-necked. Also, the wing panel appeared brownish, not as light gray as shown in adult male Green Pheasant. Finally, the bird had a partial white collar, not as evident as the white collar of Ring-necked. Green Pheasant has been reported in this same area by other visitors (on eBird) since at least 2015, although I don't know if those reports were adequately documented or are valid.

Observation Details: 1 male seen very well. Was foraging on fallen leaves when a FERAL CAT appeared and tried to hunt this bird in front of us! Thankfully, the pheasant noticed it way before the cat tried anything, with its head up watching the cat. After the strike, it flew up to a branch and gave alarm calls for about 2~3 minutes, while the cat sat and waited under the tree. The park is infested with feral cats!!

He survived the hunt and seems to be surviving the difficulties of the wild world - eagles, hawks, coyotes.  When he heard the other birds feeding he sauntered in and began feeding.  The song birds make soft calls while feeding that alerts others to something good to eat.

Locality: Ponds at 93rd St and164 Ave SE, Richland Co
Observation Details: Editing the checklist to add photos and a video link of this pheasant now that hunting season has closed.  I believe it is properly identified as a partially melanistic mutant Ring-necked Pheasant.  I had seen a glimpse of this bird along the road as I passed by earlier in the day, but it disappeared into the reeds when I came back to find and photograph it.  As I was watching and photographing various shore birds from my vehicle near a pond a while later, the pictured bird flew in and landed near the pond, walking over to the edge to get a drink of water, and then foraging a little bit.  I shot these photos and a short video of the bird; you can see the video at the following Flickr link (copy and paste into your browser):  https://flic.kr/p/2nR7DZ3    The bird acted the same as a wild pheasant, so I do not believe it was pen-raised and released or stocked, but I cannot be sure.

I shot these photos and a short video of the bird; you can see the video at the following Flickr link (copy and paste into your browser):  https://flic.kr/p/2nR7DZ3    The bird acted the same as a wild pheasant, so I do not believe it was pen-raised and released or stocked, but I cannot be sure.

Have spent roughly seven hours over the past month looking for Pheasants reported recently in the Bamberg area.  Finally located at pinned location at edge of forest along roadside.  At a time when the status of RNPH in Ontario is of question, I think the following points are necessary to justify a self-sustaining population. This is by no means conclusive evidence and will adjust report if new evidence is found. Some points towards a naturalized exotic:  -	Nearest known Pheasantry (Creekside Pheasantry) is located 10 km away and no evidence of captive birds from local homeowners -	From eBird and word of mouth, male and females have occurred in all seasons in this region since the 80’s and possibly earlier -	There is at least one male that has been seen three times along Moser Young Road between Bamberg and Gerber Road in the last month -	Behaviour reflective of a natural bird (very skulky, tangle jumping)  As far as I’m aware this is the last promising population of Pheasants left in Waterloo Region.

I reported a Ring-necked Pheasant in the field just off Watts Rd a week ago.  I saw this Ring-necked in the road.  I began taking photos.  I didn't want to scare it so I remained in my truck and took the photos through the windshield.  Unfortunately they are not very good.  Shooting with a telephoto lens through the windshield resulted in most of them being distorted or fuzzy (then again, it might be the photographer), but you can at least make out what I was seeing.  The Ring-necked slowly began coming up the road towards me until it was only ten to fifteen feet away.  He then crossed the road and went into the brush where I got a few more photos. This time I had my driver-side window down and the photos are much clearer, but the Ring-necked is, as you can see, in the brush.

This pheasant came across this Pacific Gopher Snake that had just killed and was attempting to swallow a rabbit. Either out of curiosity, or an attempt to protect its two nearby hens, it started pecking at the snake. The snake started spinning around and whipping its tail at the pheasant. (Having a mouthful of rabbit I would imagine the snake couldn't do much else.) Meanwhile, a Spotted Sandpiper stood nearby watching everything unfold, surely thinking "I don't want any part of this!"

Highly colored with a chicken-like walk.  Bright red wattles on face and visible white ring around the neck.  Foraging near the bird feeders and retreats to the edge of the woods when resting or frightened. This was certainly a surprise sighting, as I was looking for the painted bunting seen in that location the previous 2 mornings.  Believed to be an escapee from a group of Ring-necked pheasants raised and brought in for a hunting club.  Interestingly, this lone male did not have the long beautiful tail typically seen this species.  The absence of such leads me to believe it was one of a large group that was raised in a cage and likely transported to the area in a crowded space. See photos.

Observation Details: It was foraging in the back yard of a residence at 17th St. I caught a glimpse of it and parked behind a building. I quietly got out and eased my head around a corner to take some photos. Some woody material stuck in a fence also hid me a little. The bird was foraging on an old gravel/grass mixed parking area. I think it saw me when I tried to get a better photo but did not run/fly away. It quit pecking at the ground and froze. The tail feathers looked a little short so it may be somewhat immature. I didn't want to disturb it any further so left. I have observed some males  here in the past but at the "natural habitat" areas on the Locks property, not in a yard. See photos.

Observation Details: Adult pair, foraging in a soybean field at the intersection of Fawn Grove and Scott Rds. Dave Ziolkowski reported the male at this location yesterday. I was trying to locate the male this morning...he was nowhere in sight and wasn't calling. After about ten minutes of driving around the area, I was getting ready to leave and pulled off the road under a shady tree by the church at the corner. I played the "song" out the car window and waited. About 30 seconds had gone by when I heard the lovely response from the male...it's a pretty ugly sound, but it must work for him...when I finally spotted him he had a female companion in tow. As soon as I got close enough to get a couple quick photos out the window, they were off into the farther reaches of the soy bean field. They'd disappear for a bit, then stick their heads up high enough to be seen above the green.

Observation Details: Continuing in high numbers in this area as first reported by Stefan M yesterday, probably looking for an easier place to travel/feed due to the amount of snow that fell. Not very shy about staying on the road when cars go by. Observed relatively close by in all directions from the intersection, on the road, sides of the roads, in trees, and in the nearby fields.

Foraging on the roadside 2 days after a heavy snow...saw 36 more for a total of 52 (probably more) on Scallop Pond Road at 1 p.m. I observed and photographed these Pheasants for about a half hour before they headed west into the forest. Therefore I am confident that these were not included in my count of 36. Total of 52 plus more probable. Will post 36 as separate ebird entry.

Birds of the day! Despite their non-native status, RNPH's are visually stunning and always a treat to encounter! The exact origins of these two individuals are a mystery considering Ring-necked Pheasant populations are not known to be self-sustaining throughout most of Northeastern Pennsylvania with exceptions confined to locations where they are heavily stocked during the fall hunting season (i.e. Delaware Water Gap NRA). Even in these areas they remain infrequent; the majority of those that outlast hunting season often fall victim to vehicle strikes, predation, or in some cases, starvation. Due to these factors, the individuals encountered here today are believed to have been game releases from a local sportsman club. The exact date, time, and location of their potential release remains unknown.

Ever see a pheasant swim? This was a first for me. I was walking on the south dike when some hunters flushed up four male pheasants. Three were shot down immediately, the fourth got away, flew over my head and over the bay. He went down in the bay and began swimming madly, but was swimming parallel to the shore instead of toward it. I watched for about 15 minutes and could see him tiring. My guess is he probably drowned. The hunters were not interested in trying  to get him, although one did climb up to see how far out he was. Said it was too far for his dog.  What a waste.

This pheasant came across this Pacific Gopher Snake that had just killed and was attempting to swallow a rabbit. Either out of curiosity, or an attempt to protect its two nearby hens, it started pecking at the snake. The snake started spinning around and whipping its tail at the pheasant. (Having a mouthful of rabbit I would imagine the snake couldn't do much else.) Meanwhile, a Spotted Sandpiper stood nearby watching everything unfold, surely thinking "I don't want any part of this!"

Observation Details: For several years we've been seeing Ring-necked Pheasants along Old Vinton Road near Prairie Wildlife northeast of West Point and know that they release some every year for hunters staying at their lodge. This pheasant I was surprised to see back in March 2016 at the Overlook of Columbus Lake near the Tombigbee Waterway Lock and Dam there. The two areas are only about 15 miles apart if the bird traveled in a fairly straight path from Old Vinton Road to the Columbus Lake area, so I assumed this bird had traveled from there. I'll add some photos I took back on March 12, 2016. I've never seen a pheasant again in that area. But when we bird on Old Vinton Road, we usually see 2 or 3 pheasants along the road, both male and female. So we wonder if there is any chance they have begun nesting in the wild in that area.

Locality: Salt Marsh Nature Center at Marine Park
Observation Details: The first bird was a female in the SE corner of the grassland, watched her fly from the grass area into the edge of the woods as I came out of the trail that goes alongside the golf course. Walked up to the NE corner (at the edge of the forest regeneration), where I saw the next three birds together. Was watching and photographing the male when two female-type birds emerged from the grass. The craziest part of this encounter was that as I was watching the pheasants I noticed there was also a feral cat sitting about five feet away from them (social distancing!). I was of course worried by this at first, but the cat was smaller than the birds and as they approached it stood up and walked away. (flagged for count)
